{{italic title}} {{Infobox artwork | image_file = Healing of Abiku Children Twins Seven-Seven.jpg | painting_alignment = | image_size = 250px | title = Healing of Abiku Children | alt = | other_language_1 = | other_title_1 = | other_language_2 = | other_title_2 = | artist = Twins Seven-Seven | year = {{Start date|1973}} | height_metric = 130.5 | width_metric = 131 | length_metric = | height_imperial = | width_imperial = | length_imperial = | diameter__metric = | diameter_imperial = | imperial_unit = in | metric_unit = cm | city = [[Indianapolis]] | museum = [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]] | owner = }}
'''''Healing of Abiku Children''''' is a piece created by the [[Nigerian]] artist [[Twins Seven-Seven]] in 1973, located in the [[Indianapolis Museum of Art]], which is in [[Indianapolis]], [[Indiana]], [[United States of America]]. It consists of a large wooden plaque intricately carved and dyed with pigment to depict an important [[Yoruba people|Yoruba]] ceremony. In it, a mother consults with a priest to keep her ''[[abiku]]'' twins in this world, rather than dying and being reborn to her over and over.<ref name=ima/>
==Description== Twins Seven Seven was intimately familiar with the ritual he depicted, being the sole surviving child of seven sets of twins. The Yoruba are both blessed with an unusually high incidence of twins and cursed with high infant mortality, a fact which they explain with the concept of abiku, or children born to die shortly thereafter.{{cn|date=December 2017}} To end the cycle, mothers consult special divination priests, who use ceremonies and medicines to convince the children to remain in the community. The predominant figure in this work is such a mother, who holds one of her abiku twins while the other sleeps on her back. To the left, the priest framed by the door mixes the potions he will use on the children.<ref name=jama/> Every inch of space is filled by people busily performing various tasks, their large eyes and facial scarification matching traditional Yoruba ideals of beauty. Twins Seven Seven's unique combination of modern and traditional styles (he was trained by German artists in Nigeria) is on display in this work, with its intricate, rhythmic designs from edge to edge and an almost sculptural quality due to the combination of carving and coloring the wood.<ref name=lee>{{cite book|last1=Lee|first1=Ellen Wardwell|last2=Robinson|first2=Anne|title=Indianapolis Museum of Art: Highlights of the Collection|publisher=Indianapolis Museum of Art|location=Indianapolis|year=2005|isbn=0936260777}}</ref>
===Acquisition=== ''Healing of Abiku Children'' was commissioned in 1972 by Dr. Hanus Grosz of Indianapolis, who requested a work on "healing".<ref name=jama>{{cite web|last=Southgate|first=M. Therese|title=Healing of Abiku Children|url=http://jama.jamanetwork.com/article.aspx?articleid=201614|work=[[The Journal of the American Medical Association]]|accessdate=27 September 2012|date=5 October 2005}}</ref>
In 1993, ''Healing of Abiku Children'' was given to the IMA by Mr. and Mrs. Harrison Eiteljorg. It is currently displayed in the Eiteljorg Suite of African and Oceanic Art and has the acquisition number 1993.82.<ref name=ima>{{cite web|title=Healing of Abiku Children|url=http://www.imamuseum.org/art/collections/artwork/healing-abiku-children-twins-seven-seven|publisher=[[Indianapolis Museum of Art]]|accessdate=27 September 2012}}</ref>
