'''''The Romany Rye''''' is a novel by [[George Borrow]], written in 1857 as a sequel to ''[[Lavengro]]'' (1851).

==The novel==
Largely thought to be at least partly autobiographical, ''The Romany Rye'' follows from ''Lavengro'' (1851). The title can be translated from [[Romani language|Romany]] as "Gipsy Gentleman". Mrs George Borrow wrote on 18 October 1853 to [[John Murray (publisher)|John Murray]], his publisher, saying her husband had completed his work – "which he proposes to call ''The Romany Rye – A Sequel to Lavengro.''"

The story itself follows the journey of a learned young man living with [[Romani people|Romanies]]. It is a philosophical adventure story of sorts.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=uYem-aWDd84C&dq=%22the+romany+rye%22+george+borrow Lavengro and The Romany Rye], [[Google Books]].</ref>

==In popular culture==
A pub located in Colman Road, [[Norwich]], was named ''The Romany Rye'', and later ''The Romany Beer House'' before it ceased trading in November 2008.<ref>[http://www.norfolkpubs.co.uk/norwich/rnorwich/ncrry.htm Norwich pubs] Retrieved 10 May 2012</ref> The [[Wetherspoons]] public house chain used the name ''Romany Rye'' for their pub, opened in [[Dereham]], Norfolk, in 2011. Borrow was born in the town.<ref>[http://www.jdwetherspoon.co.uk/home/pubs/the-romany-rye Wetherspoons] Retrieved 10 May 2012</ref>

